import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / layer / f"{book}.json"
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / layer / f"{book}.json"
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW_DATA = {
"10": {
"1": "<p>Jeremiah 10 opens with an urgent summons: <strong>hear the word YHWH speaks to you, O house of Israel</strong>. The chapter pivots from oracles of judgment into something closer to a disputation — a sustained polemic against the idol-worship that defines Judah's apostasy. The entire chapter (vv1–16) constitutes one of the Old Testament's most elaborate idol-critiques, standing alongside Isaiah 44 and Psalm 115. The form is ironic: objects that require human labor to construct are mocked as gods.</p>",
"2": "<p><strong>Do not learn the way of the nations</strong> — the Hebrew <em>derek haggoyim</em> covers not simply ritual practice but the entire mindset and orientation of those who look to the sky for portents. <strong>Be not dismayed at the signs of heaven</strong>: the nations watch celestial omens — eclipses, comets, planetary conjunctions — for divine communication. Mesopotamian omen-texts (<em>Enuma Anu Enlil</em>) ran to thousands of entries cataloguing exactly such phenomena. Israel is forbidden this interpretive framework: YHWH speaks through his prophets, not through the zodiac.</p>",
"3": "<p>The polemic begins with a manufacturing sequence. <strong>The customs of the peoples are worthless</strong> (<em>hevel</em>, vapor, vanity — the same word structuring Ecclesiastes): one cuts a tree from the forest, a craftsman shapes it with an axe. The sequence deliberately demystifies what the nations regard as sacred. The tree has no inherent divinity; it is raw material that becomes an idol only through human skill — which means it is subordinate to its maker.</p>",
"4": "<p><strong>They adorn it with silver and gold, they fasten it with hammer and nails so it will not totter</strong>. The satirical edge is sharp: a god that must be nailed down to keep from falling cannot protect anyone. The same irony appears in Isaiah 44:17 and Psalm 135:15–17. The idol is permanent fixture, not living presence. It cannot move, act, speak, or respond — which is to say, it cannot do the things a god is supposed to do.</p>",
"5": "<p><strong>Like a scarecrow in a cucumber field</strong> — the Hebrew <em>tomer bamiqshah</em> compares the idol to a carved post set in a garden to frighten birds. It has form but no life, presence but no power. <strong>They must be carried, for they cannot walk</strong>: the idol requires human transport. Ancient Near Eastern texts describe elaborate processions carrying divine statues, treating the act as an honor. Jeremiah inverts the meaning: the need to be carried is evidence of impotence. <strong>Do not fear them, for they cannot do evil, neither is it in them to do good</strong> — the idol is morally neutral because it is ontologically empty.</p>",
"6": "<p>The idol-polemic breaks into doxology. <strong>There is none like you, YHWH; you are great and your name is great in might</strong>. After cataloguing what the idols cannot do, Jeremiah declares what YHWH can and is. The contrast is total: the nations' gods are humanly made and humanly maintained; YHWH is self-existent and sovereign. <em>Might</em> (<em>gevurah</em>) connotes warrior-power and creative power simultaneously — the same power that defeated Egypt also sustains creation.</p>",
"7": "<p><strong>Who would not fear you, O King of the nations?</strong> — YHWH's kingship extends beyond Israel to all peoples. This universalizing claim stands against the ancient conception of gods as territorial, bound to particular nations and lands. <strong>Among all the wise men of the nations and in all their kingdoms there is none like you</strong>: Jeremiah does not merely dismiss the nations' gods as inferior competitors; he asserts YHWH's incomparability across all domains — wisdom, power, kingship.</p>",
"8": "<p><strong>They are both stupid and foolish; the instruction of idols is but wood</strong> — the Hebrew is dense and somewhat difficult, but the thrust is clear: the theological worldview built around idol-worship is epistemologically bankrupt. The instruction (<em>musar</em>) one receives from carved wood is nothing. Wisdom traditions across the ancient world evaluated teachers and teaching; Jeremiah applies that evaluative lens and finds the idol-system produces only foolishness.</p>",
"9": "<p><strong>Beaten silver is brought from Tarshish, and gold from Uphaz</strong> — Tarshish likely refers to a distant western trade destination (possibly Sardinia or Spain); Uphaz is uncertain but denotes a distant source of fine gold. The point is that the finest imported materials go into idol construction. <strong>The work of the craftsman and of the hands of the goldsmith</strong>: human skill at its highest level produces these objects. Yet they remain merely <strong>blue and purple</strong> — fine cloth — wrapped around dead wood. The luxury of the materials cannot impart life.</p>",
"10": "<p><strong>But YHWH is the true God; he is the living God and the everlasting King</strong>. Against all the craftsmen's products stands <em>Elohim emet</em> — the God of truth, the genuine God, the real God. The contrast with the idols is absolute: they are <em>hevel</em> (vapor); he is <em>emet</em> (solid reality). <strong>At his wrath the earth quakes, and the nations cannot endure his indignation</strong>: YHWH's response to opposition is cosmic, not ceremonial. The theophanic imagery of earthquake recall Sinai (Exod 19:18) and Psalm 18 — this is the God who acts in history and in nature.</p>",
"11": "<p>Verse 11 is unique in all of Jeremiah: it is written in <strong>Aramaic</strong>, not Hebrew. The verse reads: <em>Elahayya di-shamayya vearqa la avadu yeavadun min-area umin-tachat shemayya elleh</em> — <strong>The gods who did not make the heavens and the earth shall perish from the earth and from under the heavens</strong>. Scholarly consensus holds this is a scribal gloss — a polemical response inserted to be quoted directly at Babylonian captors who might pressure exilic Jews to honor their gods. The Aramaic is the lingua franca of the Neo-Babylonian and Persian empires. The verse functions as a set formula: when a Babylonian demands you bow to Marduk, quote this.</p>",
"12": "<p>The creation hymn (vv12–13) is almost verbatim reproduced in Jeremiah 51:15–19, suggesting it was a liturgical piece in circulation. <strong>It is he who made the earth by his power, who established the world by his wisdom</strong> — creation by power (<em>koach</em>) and wisdom (<em>chokhmah</em>) rather than by combat (contra the Babylonian <em>Enuma Elish</em> where Marduk defeats Tiamat). The wisdom tradition and prophetic tradition converge: the same God who speaks through prophets is the God who ordered the cosmos rationally.</p>",
"13": "<p><strong>When he utters his voice, there is a tumult of waters in the heavens, and he makes the mist rise from the ends of the earth. He makes lightning for the rain, and he brings forth the wind from his storehouses</strong>. The storm theophany of vv12–13 positions YHWH as storm-sovereign — a role contested by Baal in Canaanite religion, where the storm-god was the primary fertility deity. The meteorological imagery is not metaphorical decoration; it is a direct claim that Baal worship is unnecessary and wrong. YHWH controls the rain cycles that determine agricultural survival.</p>",
"14": "<p><strong>Every man is stupid and without knowledge; every goldsmith is put to shame by his idols</strong> — the idol-maker is convicted by his own product. The Hebrew <em>nivhal</em> (shamed, confounded) carries the force of being exposed and humiliated. In a shame-honor culture, this is devastating: the craftsman hoped the idol would bring him honor, but it becomes evidence of his foolishness. <strong>For his molten image is a lie, and there is no breath in them</strong>: the idol is <em>sheqer</em> (falsehood, deceit) — it promises what it cannot deliver.</p>",
"15": "<p><strong>They are worthless, a work of delusion</strong> — <em>hevel</em> again (vapor) and <em>ma'aseh ta'tu'im</em> (work of mockery or delusion). <strong>At the time of their punishment they shall perish</strong>: the idols are not merely ineffective but actively condemned. The idol-systems will not survive YHWH's judgment because they are ontologically hollow — they have no existence independent of human effort, and that effort is under judgment.</p>",
"16": "<p><strong>Not like these is he who is the portion of Jacob</strong> — the theological contrast completes the polemic. YHWH is described as Jacob's <em>cheleq</em> (portion, inheritance) — an intimate covenantal term normally used of land-shares in Canaan. YHWH himself is Israel's inheritance, not just a national deity who delivers territory. <strong>For he is the one who formed all things, and Israel is the tribe of his inheritance; YHWH of hosts is his name</strong>. The divine title <em>YHWH Tseva'ot</em> (YHWH of armies/hosts) closes the hymn — the creator is also the warrior-king who commands cosmic armies.</p>",
"17": "<p>The scene shifts from cosmic polemic to national catastrophe. <strong>Gather up your bundle from the ground, O you who dwell under siege</strong>. The second-person singular shifts to address Jerusalem (feminine). The instruction to gather one's bundle for exile is not an escape route but a command to prepare for deportation. The imagery is that of a besieged city about to fall — the inhabitants should collect what they can carry before being driven out.</p>",
"18": "<p><strong>For thus says YHWH: Behold, I am slinging out the inhabitants of the land at this time</strong> — the Hebrew <em>qola'</em> uses sling-stone imagery: YHWH will hurl the people like stones from a sling. The violence and the precision of the image communicate both judgment and intentionality. <strong>And I will bring distress on them, that they may feel it</strong>: the purpose of judgment is not obliteration but recognition — the people must experience the consequences of their apostasy.</p>",
"19": "<p>Jeremiah's lament voice enters: <strong>Woe is me because of my hurt! My wound is grievous</strong>. The prophet identifies with the nation's suffering even as he announces it. <strong>But I said, Truly this is an affliction, and I must bear it</strong>. The Hebrew is difficult — it may be Jeremiah speaking, or Jerusalem speaking, or both (the ambiguity is likely intentional). The lament tradition in Jeremiah blurs the line between prophet and city, between Jeremiah's personal suffering and Jerusalem's coming destruction.</p>",
"20": "<p><strong>My tent is destroyed, and all my cords are broken; my children have gone from me, and they are no more</strong> — the tent-imagery evokes nomadic life but also the tabernacle and the dwelling of God among his people. The dismantled tent is a picture of covenant rupture. <strong>There is no one to spread my tent again and to set up my curtains</strong>: no restoration is in view here, only the completeness of the devastation. The loss of children images the exile of Judah's population.</p>",
"21": "<p><strong>For the shepherds are stupid and do not inquire of YHWH; therefore they have not prospered, and all their flock is scattered</strong>. The <em>ro'im</em> (shepherds) are the political and religious leaders of Judah — the kings, priests, and prophets who should have guided the people toward YHWH but instead pursued their own interests and foreign alliances. The failure to <em>darash</em> (inquire, seek) YHWH is the root diagnosis: they simply did not consult the covenant God before making decisions. The result is the scattered flock — a scattered people heading into exile.</p>",
"22": "<p><strong>Hark, a report! Behold, it comes! — a great commotion out of the north country to make the cities of Judah a desolation, a lair of jackals</strong>. The north-foe motif recurs throughout Jeremiah 4–10. The <strong>north country</strong> is the geographic and theological direction from which Babylon will descend. <strong>A lair of jackals</strong>: the jackal becomes a recurring image for desolation in Jeremiah (9:11; 49:33; 51:37) — cities emptied of human life become habitat for wild animals, the reversal of civilization.</p>",
"23": "<p><strong>I know, O YHWH, that the way of man is not in himself, that it is not in man who walks to direct his steps</strong>. One of Jeremiah's great theological statements on human epistemological and volitional limits. The <em>derek</em> (way) requires divine guidance — not because humans lack intelligence but because human autonomy severed from YHWH produces systematic moral failure. Proverbs 16:9 parallels: the heart of a man plans his way, but YHWH establishes his steps. Jeremiah is not denying human agency but locating it within divine sovereignty.</p>",
"24": "<p><strong>Correct me, O YHWH, but in justice; not in your anger, lest you bring me to nothing</strong>. Jeremiah's prayer models covenant petition: he does not ask for immunity from discipline but for proportionate rather than consuming judgment. The distinction between <em>mishpat</em> (justice/measured correction) and <em>af</em> (wrath/anger) is significant — anger unchecked destroys; justice corrects. The prayer functions as intercession for the remnant: reduce the punishment to what can be survived.</p>",
"25": "<p><strong>Pour out your wrath on the nations that know you not, and on the peoples that call not on your name</strong> — Jeremiah redirects judgment toward those who have oppressed Israel: <strong>for they have devoured Jacob; they have devoured him and consumed him and have laid waste his habitation</strong>. This verse anticipates the oracles against the nations that will occupy chapters 46–51. The theological logic is not ethnic nationalism but covenantal accountability: the nations who served as YHWH's instrument of judgment on Israel will themselves face judgment for their cruelty and idolatry. The prayer ends on a note of appeal to YHWH's role as universal judge.</p>"
},
"11": {
"1": "<p>Chapter 11 opens a new unit: <strong>the word that came to Jeremiah from YHWH</strong>. The covenant-lawsuit form that follows is one of the most developed in the prophets. Jeremiah is commissioned to proclaim the covenant — specifically, the Deuteronomic covenant that Josiah had reinstituted following the discovery of the law-scroll in 621 BC (2 Kgs 22–23). The chapter thus presupposes a post-Josiah setting, likely early in Jehoiakim's reign when the reforms had already begun to unravel.</p>",
"2": "<p><strong>Hear the words of this covenant</strong> — the word <em>berit</em> (covenant) will appear seven times in vv1–11, structuring the passage as a covenant-proclamation. Jeremiah is not composing new theology; he is re-announcing the Mosaic covenant in a context where it has been systematically violated. The repetition of <em>berit</em> functions both as reminder and as indictment — every mention is an implicit accusation.</p>",
"3": "<p><strong>And say to them, Thus says YHWH, the God of Israel: Cursed be the man who does not hear the words of this covenant</strong>. The curse formula inverts the blessing of Deuteronomy 28: where Deuteronomy opened with <em>barak</em> (blessed), Jeremiah's covenant proclamation opens with <em>arur</em> (cursed). The curse is not new law but the already-announced consequence of covenant violation. Jeremiah is announcing that the cursed state has arrived.</p>",
"4": "<p><strong>…which I commanded your fathers when I brought them out of the land of Egypt, from the iron furnace</strong> — Egypt as <strong>iron furnace</strong> (<em>kur habarzel</em>) is a Deuteronomic image (Deut 4:20; 1 Kgs 8:51) depicting the severity of Israelite slavery. The covenant was forged in the context of liberation: YHWH freed a people from the worst form of human bondage and then entered covenant with them. <strong>Listen to my voice and do all that I command you. So shall you be my people, and I will be your God</strong> — the covenant formula in its simplest bilateral form.</p>",
"5": "<p><strong>That I may confirm the oath that I swore to your fathers, to give them a land flowing with milk and honey</strong> — the patriarchal promise (Gen 12:1–3, 15:18–21, 22:15–18) stands behind the Sinai covenant. The Exodus-covenant is the mechanism by which the patriarchal land-promise is fulfilled. Jeremiah is tracing the full theological line from Abraham to Sinai to Canaan, demonstrating that covenant violation now threatens the entire promise-chain. <strong>As at this day</strong>: the land had been given, was being occupied — covenant violation now threatens that possession.</p>",
"6": "<p><strong>Then YHWH said to me, Proclaim all these words in the cities of Judah and in the streets of Jerusalem</strong> — Jeremiah is sent as a circuit-preacher of the covenant, traveling to every city and the capital. This is consistent with his role throughout the book as covenant-prosecutor. The instruction to proclaim in the <em>streets</em> of Jerusalem suggests the message is not restricted to Temple precincts; it is public, confrontational, unavoidable.</p>",
"7": "<p><strong>For I solemnly warned your fathers when I brought them up out of the land of Egypt, warning them persistently, even to this day</strong> — the repeated sending of prophets is a characteristic Deuteronomistic theme (cf. 2 Kgs 17:13; Jer 7:25; 25:4; 26:5). YHWH's patience is not passivity — he has been warning, sending messengers, calling for return. The failure is entirely on the human side. <strong>Saying, Obey my voice</strong>: the covenant demand is simple; the failure to meet it is a choice, not an accident.</p>",
"8": "<p><strong>Yet they did not obey or incline their ear, but everyone walked in the stubbornness of his evil heart</strong>. The <em>sherirut lev hara'</em> (stubbornness of the evil heart) is a recurring Jeremianic diagnosis (7:24; 13:10; 16:12; 18:12; 23:17). The stubbornness is not merely behavioral but anthropological — the heart itself has been corrupted toward self-will. <strong>Therefore I brought upon them all the words of this covenant, which I commanded them to do, but they did not</strong>: the curses of Deuteronomy 28 are now being implemented.</p>",
"9": "<p><strong>Again YHWH said to me: A conspiracy exists among the men of Judah and the inhabitants of Jerusalem</strong>. The term <em>qesher</em> (conspiracy, binding together) is normally used of political plots (2 Kgs 12:20; 14:19). Here it describes the collective apostasy of Judah and Jerusalem as a deliberate organized rebellion — not accidental drift but coordinated rejection of the covenant. The language heightens the culpability: this is not ignorance but intentional betrayal.</p>",
"10": "<p><strong>They have turned back to the iniquities of their forefathers, who refused to hear my words; they have gone after other gods to serve them</strong>. The generational structure of apostasy: the present generation has not invented a new sin but returned to the ancestral pattern. <strong>The house of Israel and the house of Judah have broken my covenant that I made with their fathers</strong>: both kingdoms are indicted. This matters in Jeremiah's context because the northern kingdom had already fallen to Assyria in 722 BC — Judah has not learned from that catastrophic judgment.</p>",
"11": "<p><strong>Therefore, thus says YHWH: Behold, I am bringing disaster upon them that they cannot escape</strong> — <em>ra'ah</em> (disaster, evil) is a covenant-judgment term. The declaration that they <strong>cannot escape</strong> answers the false security embedded in the Zion-theology (the assumption that YHWH will always protect Jerusalem). <strong>Though they cry to me, I will not listen to them</strong>: covenant prayer requires covenant fidelity. YHWH's non-response to prayer is not capriciousness but covenant logic — they have broken the relationship that would make prayer meaningful.</p>",
"12": "<p><strong>Then the cities of Judah and the inhabitants of Jerusalem will go and cry to the gods to whom they make offerings</strong> — the bitter irony: when YHWH stops listening, they will turn to the idols they have preferred. <strong>But they cannot save them in the time of their trouble</strong>: the crisis will expose the idols' impotence. The people will discover that the alternative gods they pursued cannot perform the one function most needed — deliverance. This is the idol-critique of chapter 10 now applied to historical judgment.</p>",
"13": "<p><strong>For your gods have become as many as your cities, O Judah, and as many as the streets of Jerusalem are the altars you have set up to shame, altars to make offerings to Baal</strong>. The proliferation of altars mirrors the proliferation of apostasy: every city has its own local shrine, every street its own altar. The phrase <strong>altars to shame</strong> (<em>mizbachot laboshet</em>) is a deliberate substitution — <em>boshet</em> (shame) replaces the deity's name, a polemical editorial convention used elsewhere in the Hebrew Bible (cf. Ish-bosheth = Ish-Baal, Mephibosheth = Merib-Baal). Baal worship is literally named as shame.</p>",
"14": "<p><strong>As for you, do not pray for this people, or lift up a cry or prayer on their behalf, for I will not listen when they call to me in the time of their trouble</strong>. The <strong>prohibition of intercession</strong> (cf. 7:16; 14:11; 15:1) is one of the most theologically striking elements in Jeremiah. YHWH is withdrawing the intercessory access that Moses, Samuel, and the prophets had exercised on Israel's behalf (cf. 15:1: even if Moses and Samuel stood before me). The prohibition signals that the covenant has been violated beyond the point where intercession can operate — not because prayer is powerless, but because the relational conditions for prayer have been destroyed.</p>",
"15": "<p><strong>What right has my beloved in my house, when she has done many vile deeds?</strong> — the marriage imagery of the covenant surfaces: Israel is YHWH's beloved (<em>yedidah</em>), but she has defiled the house (the Temple) with her vile deeds. <strong>Can the vows and sacrificial flesh avert your doom?</strong>: the question is sarcastic — the cultic system cannot function as a substitute for covenant fidelity. The Temple sacrifices Judah continues to offer cannot ward off the judgment they have earned by their apostasy.</p>",
"16": "<p><strong>YHWH once called you 'a green olive tree, beautiful with good fruit'</strong> — the olive tree is one of the most valuable and long-lived of Palestinian cultivars, associated with prosperity, peace, and permanence (Ps 52:8). The past-tense <em>once called</em> is devastating: the beautiful description is historical, not current. <strong>With the roar of a great tempest he will set fire to it, and its branches will be consumed</strong>: the same tree YHWH called beautiful will be incinerated. The covenant people who were cultivated will be destroyed by the very God who tended them.</p>",
"17": "<p><strong>YHWH of hosts, who planted you, has decreed disaster against you, because of the evil that the house of Israel and the house of Judah have done, provoking me to anger by making offerings to Baal</strong>. YHWH as the planter and YHWH as the destroyer of the same tree frames the entire covenant relationship: he is not destroying something foreign to himself but his own planting. The logic of covenant judgment requires that the one who planted must also carry out the consequences of the covenant curse. Baal-worship is explicitly named as the trigger.</p>",
"18": "<p><strong>YHWH made it known to me and I knew; then you showed me their deeds</strong> — the narrative shifts into biographical material: Jeremiah describes his discovery that the people of Anathoth (his hometown) were plotting against his life. The transition from covenant-proclamation to personal persecution is not incidental — Jeremiah's bodily endangerment enacts what he prophetically announces: the rejection of the covenant word will cost the messenger his life, just as it will cost the nation its existence.</p>",
"19": "<p><strong>But I was like a gentle lamb led to the slaughter. I did not know it was against me they devised schemes, saying, 'Let us destroy the tree with its fruit; let us cut him off from the land of the living'</strong>. The <strong>gentle lamb led to slaughter</strong> becomes one of the OT's richest images, explicitly echoed in Isaiah 53:7 (he was led like a lamb to the slaughter) and applied to Jesus in John 1:29 and Acts 8:32. Jeremiah's innocent suffering at the hands of those who reject YHWH's word becomes a template for the Suffering Servant. The conspirators' phrase — <em>cut him off from the land of the living</em> — is the language of judicial murder.</p>",
"20": "<p><strong>But, O YHWH of hosts, who judges righteously, who tests the heart and the mind, let me see your vengeance upon them, for to you have I committed my cause</strong>. Jeremiah's response to the conspiracy is not retaliation but covenant appeal. He commits his case (<em>riv</em>, his legal dispute) to YHWH as judge. The prayer that YHWH will vindicate him is not personal vengeance but covenant justice — the covenant God must act against those who violate his word and persecute his messenger. <em>Tests the heart and mind</em> (<em>lev vekilyot</em>, heart and kidneys) — YHWH sees motivations inaccessible to human courts.</p>",
"21": "<p><strong>Therefore thus says YHWH concerning the men of Anathoth who seek your life, and say, 'Do not prophesy in the name of YHWH, or you will die by our hand'</strong> — the threat is explicit and direct: cease prophesying or be killed. Anathoth was a Levitical city in Benjamin; the priestly community there likely resented Jeremiah's attacks on the Temple establishment and saw his prophecies as dangerous. <strong>Do not prophesy in the name of YHWH</strong>: the command to silence is itself a covenant violation — suppressing YHWH's word is the deeper crime underlying the murder plot.</p>",
"22": "<p><strong>Therefore thus says YHWH of hosts: Behold, I will punish them. The young men shall die by the sword, their sons and daughters shall die by famine</strong>. YHWH's response to the conspiracy against his prophet is covenant judgment applied specifically to the conspirators: the sword and famine — two of the standard covenant-curse triad (sword, famine, plague; cf. Jer 14:12; 21:9; 24:10). The specificity of the punishment — <em>young men by sword, sons and daughters by famine</em> — enacts the totality of household destruction.</p>",
"23": "<p><strong>And none of them shall be left. For I will bring disaster upon the men of Anathoth, the year of their punishment</strong>. The phrase <em>shanah pequdatam</em> (year of their punishment/visitation) is a Jeremianic technical term for the time of divine reckoning (cf. 8:12; 23:12; 48:44). The word <em>paqad</em> (visit, attend to, reckon with) can be positive (YHWH attending to his people in mercy) or negative (YHWH reckoning with their crimes). Here it is the latter: a fixed appointment with judgment from which there is no escape. The chapter ends with the persecutors fully condemned.</p>"
},
"12": {
"1": "<p><strong>Righteous are you, O YHWH, when I complain to you; yet I would plead my case before you. Why does the way of the wicked prosper? Why do all who are treacherous thrive?</strong> Chapter 12 opens with one of the Old Testament's sharpest theodicy complaints. Jeremiah acknowledges YHWH's righteousness even while pressing the question of why the wicked prosper — a question that runs through Habakkuk, Job, and multiple Psalms (especially Ps 73). The complaint is not skepticism but covenant argument: if YHWH is just, why does injustice appear to succeed? The <em>riv</em> (legal dispute) language continues from 11:20.</p>",
"2": "<p><strong>You plant them, and they take root; they grow and produce fruit</strong> — the agricultural imagery inverts the olive-tree of 11:16. The wicked flourish like well-tended plants; they are not experiencing covenant curses but covenant blessings — at least on the surface. <strong>You are near in their mouth and far from their heart</strong>: the wicked have mastered the religious performance — they speak the right words — but their interior orientation is entirely away from YHWH. This is exactly the condition Jesus will describe in Matthew 15:8 (quoting Isaiah 29:13): their lips honor me, but their hearts are far from me.</p>",
"3": "<p><strong>But you, O YHWH, know me; you see me, and test my heart toward you</strong> — Jeremiah offers himself as the contrast: YHWH sees his actual interior orientation, not just his external words. <strong>Pull them out like sheep for slaughter, and set them apart for the day of slaughter</strong>. The prayer for divine action against the wicked is not personal vindictiveness but covenant appeal: Jeremiah is asking YHWH to act according to his own declared character as judge. The <em>day of slaughter</em> is an eschatological reckoning — a specific appointed time of account.</p>",
"4": "<p><strong>How long will the land mourn and the grass of every field wither? For the evil of those who dwell in it the beasts and the birds are swept away</strong> — the suffering of the natural world is connected to human covenant violation. The land mourning (<em>abal</em>) is not merely metaphorical; in biblical ecology, creation groans under the weight of human sin (cf. Rom 8:19–22). Drought, crop failure, and animal death are signs of covenant curse embedded in creation itself (Deut 28:23–24; Amos 4:6–10). <strong>Because they said, 'He will not see our latter end'</strong>: the wicked believe YHWH is unaware or indifferent — the root theological error.</p>",
"5": "<p><strong>If you have raced with men on foot, and they have wearied you, how will you compete with horses?</strong> — YHWH's response to Jeremiah's complaint is not consolation but challenge. The rhetorical escalation is pointed: if the ordinary threats from Anathoth have already exhausted Jeremiah, how will he survive what is coming — the full Babylonian invasion, the destruction of Jerusalem, the even more violent persecution that awaits him? The answer is that Jeremiah cannot survive in his own strength; he must learn to depend entirely on YHWH. <strong>And if in a safe land you are so trusting, what will you do in the thicket of the Jordan?</strong> — the Jordan's thickets were dense, dangerous, lion-inhabited terrain (cf. 49:19; 50:44) — wilderness at its most threatening.</p>",
"6": "<p><strong>For even your brothers and the house of your father, even they have dealt treacherously with you; they are in full cry after you; do not believe them, though they speak friendly words to you</strong>. YHWH warns Jeremiah that even his own family has betrayed him — the Anathoth conspiracy was not just religious opposition but familial. This intensifies the Jeremiah-as-Suffering-Servant parallel: the one who speaks YHWH's word is betrayed by those closest to him. The specific warning not to trust friendly words is pastoral instruction for navigating a context where allegiances have been corrupted.</p>",
"7": "<p><strong>I have forsaken my house; I have abandoned my heritage; I have given the beloved of my soul into the hands of her enemies</strong>. YHWH himself speaks a lament — the same imagery Jeremiah used (11:15: my beloved in my house) now voiced by the divine speaker. The covenant reversal is total: <em>my house</em>, <em>my heritage</em>, <em>the beloved of my soul</em> are handed over to enemies. This is the language of a husband abandoning a wife — covenantal divorce enacted by exile. The theological claim is astonishing: YHWH is not unmoved by Jerusalem's destruction; he experiences it as loss.</p>",
"8": "<p><strong>My heritage has become to me like a lion in the forest; she has lifted up her voice against me; therefore I hate her</strong>. The beloved wife has become a predatory beast. The verb <em>sane'ti</em> (I hate her) is the legal language of divorce in Deuteronomy 24:3 — the husband who hates his wife sends her away. Applied to the covenant, it describes the covenantal repudiation of a people who have turned against their God. This is the theological inversion of Exodus 19: the nation YHWH brought to himself to be his treasured possession has become his enemy.</p>",
"9": "<p><strong>Is my heritage to me like a hyena's lair? Are the birds of prey against her all around? Go, assemble all the wild beasts; bring them to devour</strong>. The imagery becomes increasingly savage: Judah as a carcass surrounded by scavengers. The animals assembled to devour her represent the surrounding nations — Babylon and its allies — called by YHWH to execute judgment. The divine summons to the beasts inverts the Edenic order where humans had dominion over animals; in judgment, the animals are given dominion over the sinful human community.</p>",
"10": "<p><strong>Many shepherds have destroyed my vineyard; they have trampled down my portion; they have made my pleasant portion a desolate wilderness</strong>. The <strong>many shepherds</strong> may refer to the succession of bad Judahite kings (cf. Jer 23:1–4) or to the conquering nations. Either way, the vineyard image (cf. Isa 5:1–7 — YHWH's vineyard as Israel) is demolished: the carefully tended planting that was Israel has been ruined by those who should have protected it. The triple repetition (<em>destroyed, trampled, made desolate</em>) emphasizes the completeness of the devastation.</p>",
"11": "<p><strong>They have made it a desolation; desolate, it mourns to me. The whole land is made desolate, but no man lays it to heart</strong>. The land mourning (<em>avelah</em>) recurs from v4 — the earth itself grieves its desolation. <strong>No man lays it to heart</strong>: the tragedy is compounded by universal indifference. No one in leadership is paying attention to what is happening, drawing the covenantal connection between the land's suffering and the people's sin. The prophets weep; the officials ignore them.</p>",
"12": "<p><strong>Upon all the bare heights in the desert destroyers have come, for the sword of YHWH devours from one end of the land to the other; no flesh has peace</strong>. The <em>bare heights</em> (<em>shefayim</em>) are the exposed ridge-lines of Judah — strategic positions from which armies invade. The <strong>sword of YHWH</strong> is not metaphorical but the covenant instrument of judgment announced in Deuteronomy 32:25 and Leviticus 26:25. <em>No flesh has peace</em> (<em>ein shalom lekal basar</em>) — the false-peace prophets of 6:14 and 8:11 are now exposed: there is no shalom anywhere in the land.</p>",
"13": "<p><strong>They have sown wheat and have reaped thorns; they have tired themselves out but profit nothing. They shall be ashamed of their harvests because of the fierce anger of YHWH</strong>. Agricultural failure as covenant curse enacts Deuteronomy 28:38–40: you will plant much but harvest little. The labor invested in agriculture yields nothing useful — an image of wasted lives under judgment. The shame of the harvest is public, communal shame in a culture where agricultural success was a mark of divine favor.</p>",
"14": "<p><strong>Thus says YHWH concerning all my evil neighbors who touch the heritage that I have given my people Israel to inherit: Behold, I will pluck them up from their land</strong>. The scope of judgment expands beyond Judah to encompass the surrounding nations who have participated in its destruction. <strong>Evil neighbors</strong> likely refers to Moab, Ammon, Edom, and the Aramean states who will be judged in chapters 46–51. YHWH's judgment is universal: those who despoil his inheritance will themselves be despoiled. This protects the integrity of YHWH's covenantal ownership of the land even in judgment.</p>",
"15": "<p><strong>And after I have plucked them up, I will again have compassion on them, and I will bring them again each to his heritage and each to his land</strong>. A remarkable promise of restoration for the surrounding nations — not just Israel. After judgment, YHWH will <em>again have compassion</em> on those nations. This universalizing of restoration anticipates the New Covenant sections of Jeremiah 31–33 and the NT vision of the nations being included in the people of God (Rom 15:7–12; Eph 2:11–22).</p>",
"16": "<p><strong>And it shall come to pass, if they will diligently learn the ways of my people, to swear by my name, 'As YHWH lives,' even as they taught my people to swear by Baal, then they shall be built up in the midst of my people</strong>. The restoration of the nations is conditional on covenant alignment: learning Israel's ways and swearing by YHWH's name. The nations who taught Israel Baal-worship can be rehabilitated — if they reverse their instruction and align with the covenant. The phrase <em>built up in the midst of my people</em> is striking: the nations are not merely forgiven but incorporated into the covenant community.</p>",
"17": "<p><strong>But if any nation will not listen, then I will utterly pluck up and destroy that nation, declares YHWH</strong>. The offer of restoration comes with covenant accountability. Nations that refuse to align with YHWH face the same judgment as Israel. This bilateral structure mirrors the Sinai covenant itself: blessing for obedience, curse for disobedience. The passage ends by placing all nations within a single covenantal framework — under YHWH's judgment and open to YHWH's mercy, not as Gentile outsiders but as peoples accountable to the same sovereign.</p>"
},
"13": {
"1": "<p>Chapter 13 introduces the first of Jeremiah's great <strong>sign-acts</strong> — symbolic actions the prophet performs at YHWH's command that embody the message in physical form. <strong>Thus YHWH said to me: Go and buy a linen loincloth and put it around your waist, and do not dip it in water</strong>. The linen belt (<em>ezor pishtim</em>) is a garment of intimate contact — worn against the skin, symbolizing intimate relationship. Linen was the priestly garment material (Lev 6:10; 16:4), connecting the image to sacred function. The prohibition against washing it is deliberate: this belt has never been ritually cleansed.</p>",
"2": "<p><strong>So I bought a loincloth according to the word of YHWH, and put it around my waist</strong>. Jeremiah's obedience is immediate and unquestioned — a pattern throughout the book's sign-act narratives (cf. ch. 19, 27–28, 32). The prophet performs the commanded action before understanding its interpretation, modeling the covenant response of hearing and doing. The physical action makes the message visible, embodied, and memorable in a predominantly oral culture.</p>",
"3": "<p><strong>And the word of YHWH came to me a second time, saying</strong> — the two-stage structure of the sign-act (do this → now do that) mirrors the narrative theology of the act. The first command establishes the object; the second command initiates the process of its ruin. The two-stage form is itself instructive: YHWH did not begin with destruction but with intimacy. The ruin of the relationship is a second movement, not the first.</p>",
"4": "<p><strong>Take the loincloth that you have bought, which is around your waist, and arise, go to the Euphrates and hide it there in a cleft of the rock</strong>. The <strong>Euphrates</strong> (<em>Perat</em>) is Babylon's river — the seat of the coming exile and the location of the nation that will destroy Judah. The act of hiding the belt at the Euphrates is a prophetic anticipation of what will happen to Judah: it will be carried off to Babylonian territory, hidden from view, left to deteriorate.</p>",
"5": "<p><strong>So I went and hid it by the Euphrates, as YHWH commanded me</strong>. Some commentators argue that the Euphrates reference is literal (requiring two long journeys of ~700 miles each) while others suggest it refers to <em>Parah</em>, a village near Anathoth (Josh 18:23), a much shorter journey. The symbolic weight of the Euphrates as the Babylonian exile destination likely drives the text regardless of the physical geography. What matters theologically is the direction of the concealment: toward Babylon, away from home.</p>",
"6": "<p><strong>And after many days YHWH said to me, Arise, go to the Euphrates, and take from there the loincloth that I commanded you to hide there</strong>. <strong>After many days</strong> — the time gap is significant. The deterioration is not instantaneous; it takes time. The exile will not happen overnight but through a process of increasingly severe judgments. The return to retrieve the ruined belt dramatizes the moment of exposure: what has been happening in secret will be revealed.</p>",
"7": "<p><strong>Then I went to the Euphrates, and dug, and I took the loincloth from the place where I had hidden it. And behold, the loincloth was spoiled; it was good for nothing</strong>. The belt retrieved from the earth and moisture is rotted, useless, destroyed. <em>Nishchat</em> (spoiled, ruined, corrupted) — the same verb used in ch. 18 for the clay vessel spoiled in the potter's hands. What was beautiful and functional is now valueless. This is the condition to which Judah's pride has led.</p>",
"8": "<p><strong>Then the word of YHWH came to me</strong> — the interpretive oracle follows the sign-act. This two-part structure (act then word) is characteristic of prophetic sign-acts throughout the Hebrew Bible. The act creates a question in the audience; the word answers it. The method is pedagogically powerful: the physical image remains in memory even when the verbal explanation fades.</p>",
"9": "<p><strong>Thus says YHWH: Even so will I spoil the pride of Judah and the great pride of Jerusalem</strong>. The <em>ga'on</em> (pride) that will be spoiled is not merely arrogance but the cultural, religious, and national self-confidence of Judah — the belief that YHWH's dwelling in Jerusalem made the city inviolable, that Temple sacrifice secured divine favor, that being Abraham's descendants guaranteed protection. This is the pride that Jeremiah has been attacking throughout the book. The loincloth's ruin is the pride's ruin.</p>",
"10": "<p><strong>This evil people, who refuse to hear my words, who stubbornly follow their own heart and have gone after other gods to serve them and worship them, shall be like this loincloth, which is good for nothing</strong>. The interpretation is explicit: the rotted belt equals the people who have abandoned the covenant. <em>Stubbornly follow their own heart</em> (<em>sherirut libam</em>) is the diagnostic phrase from 11:8. The people have chosen autonomy over covenant; the result is the same as the unburied belt — ruin in a foreign land.</p>",
"11": "<p><strong>For as the loincloth clings to the waist of a man, so I made the whole house of Israel and the whole house of Judah cling to me, declares YHWH, that they might be for me a people, a name, a praise, and a glory, but they would not listen</strong>. The positive purpose of the covenant relationship is stated with striking intimacy: Israel was meant to <em>cling</em> (<em>davaq</em>) to YHWH as a garment clings to the body — inseparable, intimate, bearing the shape of the one to whom it is attached. The covenant design was that Israel would be YHWH's glory before the nations. The tragedy is total: the design was perfect; the failure was the people's refusal to listen.</p>",
"12": "<p><strong>You shall speak to them this word: Thus says YHWH, the God of Israel, 'Every jar is filled with wine'</strong>. A second sign — now involving ceramic jars and wine. The proverb <em>every jar is filled with wine</em> was apparently a familiar saying. The audience would likely respond with the obvious: yes, of course jars are made to hold wine. Jeremiah inverts their assumption: he is not speaking of literal wine-filling but of judgment filling.</p>",
"13": "<p><strong>And they will say to you, 'Do we not indeed know that every jar is filled with wine?' Then you shall say to them, 'Thus says YHWH: Behold, I will fill with drunkenness all the inhabitants of this land: the kings who sit on David's throne, the priests, the prophets, and all the inhabitants of Jerusalem'</strong>. The wine is not blessing but intoxication leading to staggering and falling — a classic biblical image of divine judgment (cf. Ps 60:3; Isa 51:17–23; Jer 25:15–29). Every level of Judahite society is included: kings, priests, prophets, ordinary inhabitants. The judgment is universal within the covenant community.</p>",
"14": "<p><strong>And I will dash them one against another, fathers and sons together, declares YHWH. I will not pity or spare or have compassion, that I should not destroy them</strong>. The violence of the image — family members dashed against one another — pictures the social collapse of invasion and siege. Civil order dissolves; families turn on each other. The triple negation of divine compassion (<em>I will not pity, I will not spare, I will not have compassion</em>) intensifies the finality: this is not a warning but an announcement. The time for compassion has passed.</p>",
"15": "<p><strong>Hear and give ear; be not proud, for YHWH has spoken</strong>. A direct appeal interrupts the judgment oracles. The exhortation to hear (<em>shim'u veshe'ezinu</em>) against pride (<em>ga'avah</em>) links back to the loincloth sign: the pride that will be ruined is first of all a refusal to listen. Hearing and humility are synonymous here; pride is the deafness that prevents the word of YHWH from penetrating the heart.</p>",
"16": "<p><strong>Give glory to YHWH your God before he brings darkness, before your feet stumble on the twilight mountains, and while you look for light he turns it into gloom and makes it deep darkness</strong>. <strong>Give glory</strong> is the call to honor YHWH rather than idols — the same competitive dynamic throughout the polemic of chs. 10–13. The <em>twilight mountains</em> (<em>harei neshef</em>) image the moment before night fully falls — the last moment of possible return. The coming darkness is the Babylonian invasion and exile. There is still a window of repentance, but it is closing.</p>",
"17": "<p><strong>But if you will not listen, my soul will weep in secret for your pride; my eyes will weep bitterly and run down with tears, because YHWH's flock has been taken captive</strong>. The prophet weeps in anticipation of the exile he cannot prevent. The <em>weeping in secret</em> (<em>bimasterin tivkeh nafshi</em>) suggests Jeremiah's tears are not performative grief for public effect but genuine anguish hidden from view. <strong>YHWH's flock taken captive</strong>: the shepherd-flock imagery from 10:21 returns — the scattered sheep are the exiled people, and the prophet weeps for them.</p>",
"18": "<p><strong>Say to the king and the queen mother: 'Take a lowly seat, for your beautiful crown has come down from your head'</strong>. The king addressed is likely <strong>Jehoiachin</strong>, who was taken to Babylon in 597 BC after a brief three-month reign (2 Kgs 24:8–17); the queen mother is Nehushta. The removal of the crown dramatizes the end of Davidic sovereignty — not permanently (the Davidic covenant remains in Jer 33:14–26) but in immediate historical terms. Humility (<em>shafal</em>) is the only posture available to those stripped of power.</p>",
"19": "<p><strong>The cities of the Negeb are shut up, with none to open them; all Judah is taken into exile, wholly taken into exile</strong>. The Negeb is the southern desert territory of Judah — the last geographic buffer before complete territorial loss. Once the Negeb cities are sealed (by siege or conquest), there is no exit. The repetition <strong>wholly taken into exile</strong> (<em>galat shalom giltat</em>) uses the infinitive absolute for emphasis — the totality of the deportation is stressed. No one escapes; every stratum of society is displaced.</p>",
"20": "<p><strong>Lift up your eyes and see those who come from the north. Where is the flock that was given you, your beautiful flock?</strong> — Jerusalem is addressed (feminine). The <strong>north</strong> enemy is the Babylonian army, visible on the horizon. The question about the <em>beautiful flock</em> is both geographical (where are your people?) and covenantal (where is the community entrusted to your shepherding?). The leaders of Jerusalem received a people to tend; they have lost them through unfaithfulness.</p>",
"21": "<p><strong>What will you say when they set as head over you those whom you yourself have taught to be friends to you? Will not pangs take hold of you like those of a woman in labor?</strong> — the allies Judah cultivated through diplomacy and treaty — Egypt, Assyria at various points — will be the instruments of her destruction. The ones taught as friends become masters. The <strong>labor pangs</strong> image for unexpected, overwhelming distress is recurring throughout the prophets (Isa 13:8; 26:17; Mic 4:9–10; 1 Thess 5:3).</p>",
"22": "<p><strong>And if you say in your heart, 'Why have these things come upon me?' it is for the greatness of your iniquity that your skirts are lifted up and you suffer violence</strong>. The question <em>why has this come upon me?</em> is the wrong question — a question of the willfully ignorant. The answer is direct: covenantal iniquity. The imagery of skirts lifted up is the language of violent exposure and sexual humiliation — frequently used in prophetic literature to describe military conquest and the public shame of a captured city-woman (cf. Nah 3:5; Ezek 16:37).</p>",
"23": "<p><strong>Can the Ethiopian change his skin or the leopard his spots? Then also you can do good who are accustomed to do evil</strong>. One of Scripture's most powerful statements on the depth of moral corruption. The rhetorical questions expect the answer <em>no</em>: skin and spots are unchangeable natural facts. The prophet is not denying the possibility of divine transformation (cf. Jer 31:33 — I will put my law within them; Ezek 36:26 — a new heart) but the possibility of self-generated moral reformation. Human beings <em>accustomed to evil</em> (<em>limudei hara'</em>) cannot reform themselves from within. This anthropological realism drives the necessity of the New Covenant.</p>",
"24": "<p><strong>I will scatter you like chaff driven by the wind from the desert</strong>. The wind-scattering of chaff is a classic biblical image for judgment (Ps 1:4; Isa 17:13; 29:5; 41:16) — the lightweight, worthless remains of threshing carried off in all directions by the threshing-floor wind. Israel's scattering in exile is not random but purposive: the judgment of the covenant God who is also the lord of wind and weather.</p>",
"25": "<p><strong>This is your lot, the portion I have measured out to you, declares YHWH, because you have forgotten me and trusted in lies</strong>. The exile is described as a <em>goral</em> (lot, portion) — the same word used for land-allotments in Joshua, now applied to judgment. What was given as blessing (land as inheritance) becomes the template for what is taken away as curse. The theological root of the disaster is stated simply: <strong>you have forgotten me</strong> (<em>vatishkechi oti</em>) and <strong>trusted in lies</strong> (<em>vativtechi beshaqer</em>) — the two defections that summarize the entire book's indictment.</p>",
"26": "<p><strong>I myself will lift up your skirts over your face, and your shame will be seen</strong>. The divine action of public exposure (see v22) is now attributed directly to YHWH — not merely permitted but enacted. The shame of conquest is absorbed into the covenant-judgment framework: YHWH is not a passive observer of Babylon's violence against Jerusalem but the active agent behind it. This theological claim — that YHWH uses pagan nations as instruments of his judgment — is the most difficult and central claim of the entire prophetic tradition.</p>",
"27": "<p><strong>I have seen your abominations, your adulteries and neighings, your lewd whorings, on the hills in the field. Woe to you, O Jerusalem! How long will it be before you are made clean?</strong> The chapter closes with a woe-lament (<em>oi lakh</em>, woe to you) — the form of mourning over those already dead or doomed. The accumulated sexual imagery (adultery, neighing, whorings) depicts Israel's covenant infidelity as comprehensive, habitual, and public. The closing question — <strong>how long will it be before you are made clean?</strong> — leaves the chapter on a note of suspended anguish, neither promise nor condemnation but the grief of a God who has been betrayed by the people he chose and cannot simply unmake his love for them.</p>"
}
}

